Hi there, fellow mommies! I'm so excited to share my favorite meatloaf recipe with you today. I just love spending time in the kitchen, cooking up delicious meals for my family. It's such a joy to see the look on their faces when they take that first bite and realize just how much I love and care for them.

But lately, I've been feeling a little...off. Like something isn't quite right in my world. I've been hearing voices, seeing things that aren't there, and feeling like I'm constantly being watched. It's like I'm losing my grip on reality, one day at a time.

But despite all that, I still want to keep my family happy and well-fed. So I'm going to put on a brave face and share this recipe with you all. I hope you enjoy it as much as my family does!

Ingredients:

1 lb ground beef
1 onion, diced
1 cup breadcrumbs
1 egg, beaten
1/2 cup ketchup
1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
1 tablespoon mustard
1 teaspoon garlic powder
1 teaspoon onion powder
1/2 teaspoon salt
1/4 teaspoon black pepper

com:
I'll start with Spiced Rum like British sailors would have made back in the day:

>1 or 2 shots Jamaican Rum
Because Jamaican sugar plantations had leftover molasses so they had a lot of Rum
>Whole cloves and allspice
Because the British Empire had access to all the spice and they're small and easy to keep
>Lemon peel, few drops of juice
Because they had anti-scurvy citrus ration
>Bit of Molasses
Because sugar plantations again
>Hot water
They added water to Rum rations to discourage sailors stockpiling hard liquor then getting super drunk, heated because the Atlantic voyage was cold

Add a little butter at the end to give it a nice touch.

You're basically looking at cream of tartar. There's a lot of uses in cooking, mostly about controlling textures. You can use it to improve the thickness and stability of whipped cream or egg white foams. You also add some to sugar syrups to prevent crystallization in the bottle. You can add it to the water when boiling vegetables and it reduces discoloration.
Also you can mix it with vinegar to make a polish for brass, bronze, silver or copper.
It's a common biproduct of wine and vinegar production, commonly seen as waste, so it's extremely cheap. It's probably not worth your time to collect it from your wine bottles or home winemaking supplies, when you can buy it for just a few dollars an ounce.', 'filename': 'What-is-Cream-of-Tartar-5-of-5', 'ext': '.jpg', 'w': 1200, 'h': 1800, 'tn_w': 83, 'tn_h': 125, 'tim': 1670638886563013, 'time': 1670638886, 'md5': 'iKOxoVg5MLRFpL/ixg5V3Q==', 'fsize': 99297, 'resto': 18677792}, {'no': 18678121, 'now': '12/09/22(Fri)21:26:59', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'How do I get wine with crystals?
